Raster Data

For this example, we will import and plot the Philippine Elevation data. Data is obtained from https://data.humdata.org/dataset/philippines-elevation-model.

Importing

Use the package raster to import the *.grd file to R.

library(raster)
## Loading required package: sp
grd_file <- raster("Data/PHL_ALT/PHL_msk_alt.grd")
class(grd_file)
## [1] "RasterLayer"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "raster"

Visualization

We can plot the elevation data easily using the plot() function.

plot(grd_file)

We can convert it to a data frame or tibble for easier viewing, manipulation, and integration to tidyverse and ggplot.

elev_df <- as.data.frame(rasterToPoints(grd_file))
elev_df

Now, using ggplot to visualize the gridded dataset:

library(ggplot2)
xlabs <- c(115, 120, 125, 130)
ylabs <- c(5,10,15,20)
ggplot()+
    geom_tile(data = elev_df, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = PHL_msk_alt))+
    scale_fill_gradientn(colors = terrain.colors(5))+
    coord_fixed()+
    theme_bw()+
    theme(legend.title = element_blank(),
          legend.key.width = unit(0.3, "cm"),
          legend.key.height = unit(1.8, "cm"))+
    ggtitle("Philippine Elevation in meters")+
    xlab("LON") + ylab("LAT")+
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = xlabs, labels = paste0(xlabs,'W'))+
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = ylabs, labels = paste0(ylabs,'N'))
